	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Sun Dec 30, 2012 1:28 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: The Art Of Assembly Language</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />First things first: 6502 assembly is the least important thing you have know in order to make NES games. It's just a language, a way to communicate with the system, but knowing WHAT to communicate and HOW to communicate is much more important. Programming for the NES is like getting a job in another country: learning their language will certainly help, but it won't teach you a thing about the actual work you'll be doing.<br /><br />Anyway, assembly language is very specific, so you need a book that covers the actual CPU you'll be using, in this case the 6502, otherwise you'll just get confused. As always, I suggest you practice with the <a href="http://www.exifpro.com/utils.html" class="postlink">6502 simulator</a> to make sure you understand what each instruction does and to experiment with logic in general.<br /><br />While you study assembly, you should also study how NES games work. Use the debugging features in FCEUX to analyze how games function. Watch the pattern tables, the name tables, the sprites. Try to make some sense out of how the game is generating its visuals. Game logic is also very important. You have to learn how to do things like object AI, collision detection, physics, and so on, in order to be able to successfully simulate a world within your program.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
