		<td><b>Re: The Art Of Assembly Language</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The book that helped me get my start in assembly language in general and give me a good background for learning 6502 was &quot;Assembly Language: Step by Step.&quot; There are so many similarities between how different processors work that I don't think it really matters which one you start with (this book covers x86). The thing that makes this book shine is how it is written and how carefully and slowly it teaches the reader. The following isn't really necessary, but because I'm such a big fan of the book and how good of a teacher the author Jeff Duntemann is, I made this video advocating the book, in person: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=URku_BHIR9g" class="postlink">Assembly Language: Step by Step</a>. Could very well turn out that you don't need an introduction that is quite so friendly as this, but it sure helped me along. It might be there are others out there who would benefit from it as well. Note I made that video for Nintendoage originally, I address that site verbally in the video.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


